orning Post |access-date=31 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130183327/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/health-environment/article/3048097/long-queues-outlets-across-hong-kong-selling |archive-date=30 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> An ongoing period of panic buying has also caused many stores to be cleared of non-medical products such as bottled water, vegetables, and rice.<ref name=\"scmp3048121\">{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/society/article/3048121/china-coronavirus-shelves-cleared-essentials-spread-sparks |title=Shelves cleared as coronavirus spread sparks Hong Kong panic buying |date=29 January 2020 |website=South China Morning Post |access-date=31 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130185856/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/society/article/3048121/china-coronavirus-shelves-cleared-essentials-spread-sparks |archive-date=30 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Government of Hong Kong]] had its imports of face masks cancelled as global face mask stockpiles decline.<ref name=\"scmp3048332\">{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/health-environment/article/3048332/china-coronavirus-hongkongers-online-orders-masks |title=Mask orders cancelled as Hongkongers face overseas supply issues amid virus |date=31 January 2020 |website=South China Morning Post |access-date=31 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131031715/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/health-environment/article/3048332/china-coronavirus-hongkongers-online-orders-masks |archive-date=31 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn view of the coronavirus outbreak, the [[Education Bureau]] closed all kindergartens, primary schools, secondary schools, and special schools until 20 April.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/education/article/3075521/coronavirus-little-if-any-possibility-hong-kong-schools |title=Coronavirus: \u2018little, if any, possibility\u2019 Hong Kong schools resume fully on April 20, Lam says|website=SCMP |access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> The disruption has raised concerns over the situation of students who are due to take examinations at the end of the year, especially in light of the protest-related disruption that happened in 2019.<ref name=\"scmp3047662\">{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/education/article/3047662/china-coronavirus-hong-kong-students-face-exam-crunch |title=First protests, now virus: schools suspension could hurt those facing exams |date=26 January 2020 |website=South China Morning Post |access-date=3 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203063457/https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/education/article/3047662/china-coronavirus-hong-kong-students-face-exam-crunch |archive-date=3 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 February, flag carrier [[Cathay Pacific]] requested its 27,000 employees to voluntarily take three weeks of unpaid leave by the end of June. The airline had previously reduced flights to mainland China by 90% and overall flights by 30%.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Riley |first=Charles |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/05/business/cathay-pacific-coronavirus/index.html |title=Cathay Pacific asks workers to take 3 weeks off without pay as the coronavirus decimates travel |date=5 February 2020 |publisher=CNN |access-date=7 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206100340/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/05/business/cathay-pacific-coronavirus/index.html |archive-date=6 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome]] (SARS)\n\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Hong Kong|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.coronavirus.gov.hk/eng/index.html Together, We Fight the Virus!]\n* [https://www.chp.gov.hk/en/index.html The Centre for Health Protection]\n*{{Commons category-inline|COVID-19 pandemic in Hong Kong}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests}}\n{{HKafter1997}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by dependent territory|Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in China by city|Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:2020 in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Hong Kong]]\n", "name_user": "Onanoff", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eImplication", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Hong_Kong"}
{"title_page": "Pitt Meadows Airport", "text_new": "{{Infobox airport\n| name = Pitt Meadows Regional Airport\n| nativename = Pitt Meadows Airport\n| image=Pitt Meadows Tower (5971753372).jpg\n| IATA = <!-- YPK is not anymore the IATA code for this airport: http://www.iata.org/publications/Pages/code-search.aspx -->\n| ICAO = CYPK\n| type = Public\n| owner = \n| owner-oper = Pitt Meadows Airport Society<ref name=\"PMAS\">Transport Canada: [http://www.tc.gc.ca/programs/airports/status/menu.htm Airport Divestiture Status Report] Retrieved on 20 December 2009</ref>\n| city-served = [[Metro Vancouver]]\n| location = [[Pitt Meadows]], [[British Columbia]]\n| timezone = [[Pacific Time Zone|PST]]\n| utc = [[UTC\u221208:00]]\n| summer = PDT\n| utcs = [[UTC\u221207:00]]\n| elevation-f = 12\n| coordinates = {{coord|49|12|58|N|122|42|48|W|region:CA-BC|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map = Canada British Columbia#Canada\n| pushpin_label = CYPK\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in British Columbia\n| website = [http://www.flyypk.ca/ FlyYPK.ca]\n| r1-number = 08L/26R\n| r1-length-f = 2,485\n| r1-surface = Asphalt\n| r2-number = 08R/26L\n| r2-length-f = 5,003\n| r2-surface = Asphalt\n| r3-number = 18/36\n| r3-length-f = 2,484\n| r3-surface = Asphalt\n| stat-year = 2018\n| stat1-header = Aircraft Movements\n| stat1-data = 117,983\n| footnotes = Sources: [[Canada Flight Supplement]]<ref>{{CFS}}</ref><br>Movements from [[Statistics Canada]]<ref name=\"move\">{{cite web|url=https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/t1/tbl1/en/cv.action?pid=2310001801|title=Aircraft Movement Statistics: NAV CANADA Towers and Flight Service Stations: Annual Report (TP 577): Table 2-1 \u2014 Total aircraft movements by class of operation \u2014 NAV CANADA towers|work=statcan.gc.ca}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Pitt Meadows Airport''' {{Airport codes||CYPK}} is a [[Canada|Canadian]] [[general aviation]] airport located in the southwest of corner of [[Pitt Meadows]], [[British Columbia]]. In 2019, it was the [[List of the busiest airports in Canada|11th busiest airport in Canada]] with 142,523 aircraft movements and is the 4th busiest airport in the [[Lower Mainland]].<ref name=\"move\"/>\n\nThe first airport manager was Gordon McNeill 1966-1972. By 1972-1973, Pitt Meadows was the busiest airport in Canada with over 250,000 aircraft movements annually. But with the opening of [[Boundary Bay Airport]] in [[Delta, British Columbia]] in 1983, air traffic at Pitt Meadows Airport declined steadily.\n\nIn January 1998, the districts of [[Maple Ridge, British Columbia|Maple Ridge]] and Pitt Meadows jointly took custody from the federal government under the auspices of the Pitt Meadows Airport Society.<ref name=\"PMAS\"/>\n\nFive flight training schools are located at the airport. The airport features three asphalt runways, two helipads, IFR approaches, and a separate [[Pitt Meadows Water Aerodrome|float plane dock]] along the [[Fraser River]] The Nav Canada air traffic control tower operates from 7:00&nbsp;a.m. to 11:00&nbsp;p.m. 365 days per year.\n\nIn 2019, the airport terminal was moved to make room for construction of a new 40,000 Sq. Ft two-level terminal building expected to start in 2020.\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n\n===Scheduled Service===\n* [[Harbour Air]] \n** [[Victoria Harbour Airport|Victoria Harbour]]\n\n===Charter===\n* [[Island Express Air]]\n* AC Airways\n* Island Coastal Aviation\n* Pacific Rim Aviation Academy\n* Sierra Helicopters\n* Skylines Advertising\n* Vancity Seaplanes\n* Sky Helicopters\n\n==Flight training==\n* Pacific Rim Aviation Academy\n* Pacific Aviation Academy\n* Island Coastal Aviation\n* Classic Aviation Ltd\n* Montair Aviation\n\n{{wide image|Pitt Meadows Airport (2017).jpg|1000px|Pitt Meadows Airport (2017)}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of airports in the Lower Mainland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.flyypk.ca/ Official website]\n* [http://www.pittmeadows.bc.ca/ Pitt Meadows municipal website]\n* [http://archive.copanational.org/PlacesToFly/airport_view.php?pr_id=3&ap_id=244 Page about this airport] on [[Canadian Owners and Pilots Association|COPA's]] ''Places to Fly'' airport directory\n\n{{List of airports in Canada}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Certified airports in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Pitt Meadows]]\n[[Category:Transport in Greater Vancouver]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox airport\n| name = Pitt Meadows Regional Airport\n| nativename = Pitt Meadows Airport\n| image=Pitt Meadows Tower (5971753372).jpg\n| IATA = <!-- YPK is not anymore the IATA code for this airport: http://www.iata.org/publications/Pages/code-search.aspx -->\n| ICAO = CYPK\n| type = Public\n| owner = \n| owner-oper = Pitt Meadows Airport Society<ref name=\"PMAS\">Transport Canada: [http://www.tc.gc.ca/programs/airports/status/menu.htm Airport Divestiture Status Report] Retrieved on 20 December 2009</ref>\n| city-served = [[Metro Vancouver]]\n| location = [[Pitt Meadows]], [[British Columbia]]\n| timezone = [[Pacific Time Zone|PST]]\n| utc = [[UTC\u221208:00]]\n| summer = PDT\n| utcs = [[UTC\u221207:00]]\n| elevation-f = 12\n| coordinates = {{coord|49|12|58|N|122|42|48|W|region:CA-BC|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map = Canada British Columbia#Canada\n| pushpin_label = CYPK\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in British Columbia\n| website = [http://www.flyypk.ca/ FlyYPK.ca]\n| r1-number = 08L/26R\n| r1-length-f = 2,485\n| r1-surface = Asphalt\n| r2-number = 08R/26L\n| r2-length-f = 5,003\n| r2-surface = Asphalt\n| r3-number = 18/36\n| r3-length-f = 2,484\n| r3-surface = Asphalt\n| stat-year = 2018\n| stat1-header = Aircraft Movements\n| stat1-data = 117,983\n| footnotes = Sources: [[Canada Flight Supplement]]<ref>{{CFS}}</ref><br>Movements from [[Statistics Canada]]<ref name=\"move\">{{cite web|url=https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/t1/tbl1/en/cv.action?pid=2310001801|title=Aircraft Movement Statistics: NAV CANADA Towers and Flight Service Stations: Annual Report (TP 577): Table 2-1 \u2014 Total aircraft movements by class of operation \u2014 NAV CANADA towers|work=statcan.gc.ca}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Pitt Meadows Airport''' {{Airport codes||CYPK}} is a [[Canada|Canadian]] [[general aviation]] airport located in the southwest of corner of [[Pitt Meadows]], [[British Columbia]]. In 2019, it was the [[List of the busiest airports in Canada|11th busiest airport in Canada]] with 142,523 aircraft movements and is the 4th busiest airport in the [[Lower Mainland]].<ref name=\"move\"/>\n\nThe first airport manager was Gordon McNeill 1966-1972. By 1972-1973, Pitt Meadows was the busiest airport in Canada with over 250,000 aircraft movements annually. But with the opening of [[Boundary Bay Airport]] in [[Delta, British Columbia]] in 1983, air traffic at Pitt Meadows Airport declined steadily.\n\nIn January 1998, the districts of [[Maple Ridge, British Columbia|Maple Ridge]] and Pitt Meadows jointly took custody from the federal government under the auspices of the Pitt Meadows Airport Society.<ref name=\"PMAS\"/>\n\nFive flight training schools are located at the airport. The airport features three asphalt runways, two helipads, IFR approaches, and a separate [[Pitt Meadows Water Aerodrome|float plane dock]] along the [[Fraser River]].\n\nIn 2017, the airport completed the main runway extension from {{convert|4700|to|5000|ft|abbr=on}} in addition to other runway and safety enhancements.\n\nIn 2018, construction of a new [[Nav Canada]] [[control tower]] was completed, operating from 7:00&nbsp;a.m. to 11:00&nbsp;p.m. 365 days per year.\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n\n===Scheduled Service===\n* [[Harbour Air]] \n** [[Victoria Harbour Airport|Victoria Harbour]]\n\n===Charter===\n* [[Island Express Air]]\n* AC Airways\n* Island Coastal Aviation\n* Pacific Rim Aviation Academy\n* Sierra Helicopters\n* Skylines Advertising\n* Vancity Seaplanes\n* Sky Helicopters\n\n==Flight training==\n* Pacific Rim Aviation Academy\n* Pacific Aviation Academy\n* Island Coastal Aviation\n* Classic Aviation Ltd\n* Montair Aviation\n\n{{wide image|Pitt Meadows Airport (2017).jpg|1000px|Pitt Meadows Airport (2017)}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of airports in the Lower Mainland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.flyypk.ca/ Official website]\n* [http://www.pittmeadows.bc.ca/ Pitt Meadows municipal website]\n* [http://archive.copanational.org/PlacesToFly/airport_view.php?pr_id=3&ap_id=244 Page about this airport] on [[Canadian Owners and Pilots Association|COPA's]] ''Places to Fly'' airport directory\n\n{{List of airports in Canada}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Certified airports in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Pitt Meadows]]\n[[Category:Transport in Greater Vancouver]]\n", "name_user": "Schwarz777", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2020:Added note about new terminal building.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pitt_Meadows_Airport"}
{"title_page": "Kinneret (archaeological site)", "text_new": "{{coord|32|51|38|N|35|30|26|E|display=title}}\n[[File:Tell el-Oreme (Kinneret) von Westen.jpg|thumb|Tel Kinrot]]\n\n\n'''Kinneret''' ({{Lang-he-n|\u05db\u05b4\u05bc\u05e0\u05b6\u05bc\u05e8\u05b6\u05ea}}) is the name of an important [[Bronze Age|Bronze]] and [[Iron Age]] city situated on the northwestern shore of the [[Sea of Galilee]], mentioned in the [[Old Testament]] and [[New Testament]], and in the [[Danel|Aqhat Epic]] of [[Ugarit]]. Older Bible translations name Kinneret alternatively '''Kinnereth''' or '''Chinnereth''', and sometimes in the plural as '''Chinneroth'''.<ref name=\"biblehub\">{{cite web|url=http://biblehub.com/topical/c/chinneroth.htm|website=biblehub.com|title=Bible Hub, ''Chinneroth'' |accessdate=2018-11-06}}</ref> The name became '''Gennesaret''' and '''Ginosar''' ({{Lang-he-n|\u05d2\u05b4\u05bc\u05e0\u05b5\u05bc\u05d9\u05e1\u05b7\u05e8}}). The remains of Kinneret have been excavated at a site called '''Tell el-'Oreimeh''' in [[Arabic]] and '''Tel Kinrot''' in [[Modern Hebrew]].\n\n==Etymology==\nKinneret, in the plural Kinnerot, was [[Grecized]] to Gennesaret, and Ginosar is yet another transformation of the name.<ref name=\"Easton\">Easton's Revised Bible Dictionary, [https://www.biblestudytools.com/dictionary/gennesaret  \"Gennesaret\"]</ref> According to the [[Jerusalem Talmud]] (Megillah 1:1), the name Kinneret is derived from the name of the ''kinnar'' trees which grow in its vicinity, explained by lexicographer [[M. Jastrow]] to mean the Christ's thorn jujube ([[Ziziphus spina-christi]]),<ref>Marcus Jastrow, ''Dictionary of the Targumim, the Talmud Babli and Yerushalmi, and the Midrashic Literature'', Peabody, Mass. 2006, p. 651 (s.v. '''\u05db\u05e0\u05e8\u05d0''')</ref> and by [[Moses Margolies]] to mean cane reeds.<ref>Jerusalem Talmud, ''Megillah'' 1:1 [2b]</ref> Others say that it is so-called because its fruits are as sweet as those of the ''kinnara'' (Ziziphus spina-christi).<ref>[[Babylonian Talmud]] (''Megillah'' 6a)</ref>\n\n===The lake===\nDue to its prominence, the city gave its name to the lake (the \"[[Sea of Galilee]]\") for long periods of history, as the Sea of Kinneret, Kinnerot, Gennesaret, or Ginosar.<ref name=\"Easton\"/> As other places around the lake rose to prominence, such as [[Tiberias]] and [[Khirbat al-Minya|Qasr al-Minya]], the name of the lake also changed to Lake Tiberias or Lake Minya.\n\n===The plain===\nThe name has also been used for the \"Plain of Gennesaret\", which stretches south of the ancient city. The plain's modern names are Plain of Ginosar in Hebrew and el-Ghuweir in Arabic.\n\n===Modern settlements===\nThe Israeli [[kibbutz]] [[Ginosar]] derives its name from the ancient town, though it is not located on its precise site. The settlements of [[Kinneret, Israel|Moshavat Kinneret]] and [[Kvutzat Kinneret]] are even further south, on the southwestern shore of the lake.\n\n==In the Bible==\nKinneret was a town allotted to the tribe of GAD ({{Bibleref2|Joshua 19:35}}). The name appears in the singular form as \"Kinneret\" ({{Bibleref2|Numbers 34:11}}, {{Bibleref2|Deuteronomy 3:17}}) or in the plural as \"Kinneroth\" ({{Bibleref2|Joshua 11:2, 12:3}}). In the [[New Testament]] the name appears changed to Gennesaret ({{Bibleref2|Luke 5:1}}).\n\nThis city or area is also a place where [[Jesus]] visited and performed healing.<ref>Matthew 14:34; Mark 6:53</ref> To quote from the Douay-Rheims Bible, which uses the form \"Genesar\" (see [[Gospel of Matthew]]),\n:[34] And having passed the water, they came into the country of Genesar. \n:[35] And when the men of that place had knowledge of him, they sent into all that country, and brought to him all that were diseased. \n:[36] And they besought him that they might touch but the hem of his garment. And as many as touched, were made whole.  ([http://drbo.org/chapter/47014.htm Matthew 14]:34-36).\n:\n:\n:\n:\n:\n\n==Other sources==\n{{hiero|knn\ua723rtw<ref name = Gauthier205/><ref name = Budge1048>{{cite book |last1=Wallis Budge |first1=E. A. |title=An Egyptian hieroglyphic dictionary: with an index of English words, king list and geological list with indexes, list of hieroglyphic characters, coptic and semitic alphabets, etc. Vol II |date=1920 |publisher=[[John Murray (publisher)|John Murray]] |page=[https://archive.org/details/egyptianhierogly02budguoft/page/1048 1048] |url=https://archive.org/details/egyptianhierogly02budguoft}}</ref>|<center><hiero>V31:N35-N35:G1-D21:Z1-X1-G43</hiero></center>|era=nk|align=right}}\nKinneret is mentioned as '''Kennartou''' in the [[Annals of Thutmose III]] at [[Temple of Karnak]].<ref name = Gauthier205>{{cite book |last1=Gauthier |first1=Henri |title=Dictionnaire des Noms G\u00e9ographiques Contenus dans les Textes Hi\u00e9roglyphiques Vol. 5 |date=1928 |page=205 |url=https://archive.org/details/Gauthier1928/page/n105}}</ref> [[Josephus|Flavius Josephus]], as well as the [[Babylonian Talmud]] mention the lake by the name \"Sea of Ginosar\" after the small fertile plain of Ginosar that lies at the foot of Tell el-'Oreimeh, ancient Kinneret. Josephus refers to the area as having very rich soil.<ref>''The Physical Geography, Geology, and Meteorology of the Holyand'' by [[Henry Baker Tristram]] 2007 {{ISBN|1593334826}} page 11</ref>\n\n==Identification and location==\n[[File:Grimm, J.L. Mahlmann, H. Tiberias. 1850-3.jpg|thumb|The Plain of Gennesaret marked on an 1850 German map of the Sea of Galilee as \"El-Ghuweir / Genezareth\" (western shore, stretching from \"[[Khirbat al-Minya|Khan Minyeh]]\" to \"el-Mejdel / Magdala\")]]\nThe site of the fortified [[Bronze Age|Bronze]] and [[Iron Age]] city of Kinneret is identified with the mound known in Arabic as Tell el-'Oreimeh and in modern Hebrew as Tel Kinrot, halfway between [[Capernaum]] and [[Magdala]].<ref name=Negev>{{cite book |editor=Avraham Negev, Shimon Gibson |year=2001 |title=Archaeological Encyclopedia of the Holy Land |location=New York, London |publisher=Continuum |page=285 |isbn=0-8264-1316-1 }}</ref><ref>Lamar Williamson 1983 ''Mark'' {{ISBN|0804231214}} pages 129-130</ref> Situated on an important trade route, its elevated position meant that it also overlooked and guarded the Plain of Ginosar from its northern end.\n\nThe [[Tell (archaeology)|tell]] is being excavated as part of a large archaeological project which is ongoing since 2002.<ref name=\"kinneret-excavations\">{{cite web|url=http://kinneret-excavations.org/?page_id=54|title=Tel Kinrot &#8211; Kinneret Regional Project|website=kinneret-excavations.org|accessdate=2018-11-06}}</ref> It has the [[Israeli Cassini Soldner|ICS Coordinates]]: 200805-1252830;<ref name=aharoni>[[Yohanan Aharoni|Aharoni, Yochanan]]. ''The Land of the Bible, A Historical Geography''. The Westminster Press, Philadelphia, 1979, p. 433.</ref><ref name=\"amudanan\">{{cite web|url=http://amudanan.co.il/|title=\u05e2\u05de\u05d5\u05d3 \u05e2\u05e0\u05df - \u05d4\u05de\u05d3\u05e8\u05d9\u05da \u05d4\u05e9\u05d9\u05ea\u05d5\u05e4\u05d9 \u05dc\u05d9\u05d3\u05d9\u05e2\u05ea \u05d4\u05d0\u05e8\u05e5|website=amudanan.co.il|lang=he|accessdate=2018-11-06}}</ref><ref name=coordinate-converter /> ca. 32.87000 N, 35.539312 E.<ref name=coordinate-converter>{{cite web|url=http://twcc.free.fr/|author=Cl\u00e9ment RONZON|website=twcc.free.fr|title=TWCC, The World Coordinate Converter|accessdate=2018-11-06}}</ref>\n\n\n==See also==\n*[[Cities in the Book of Joshua]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[[Easton's Bible Dictionary (1897)]]\n*[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/06415a.htm Catholic Encyclopedia]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|Tel Kinarot}}\n*[http://kinneret-excavations.org/?page_id=54 Tel Kinrot page on the website of the \"Kinneret Regional Project\" international archaeological expedition]\n\n{{New Testament places associated with Jesus}}\n\n[[Category:New Testament places]]\n[[Category:Hebrew Bible places]]\n[[Category:Former populated places in Southwest Asia]]\n[[Category:Tells]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord|32|51|38|N|35|30|26|E|display=title}}\n[[File:Tell el-Oreme (Kinneret) von Westen.jpg|thumb|Tel Kinrot]]\n\n\n'''Kinneret''' ({{Lang-he-n|\u05db\u05b4\u05bc\u05e0\u05b6\u05bc\u05e8\u05b6\u05ea}}) is the name of an important [[Bronze Age|Bronze]] and [[Iron Age]] city situated on the northwestern shore of the [[Sea of Galilee]], mentioned in the [[Old Testament]] and [[New Testament]], and in the [[Danel|Aqhat Epic]] of [[Ugarit]]. Older Bible translations name Kinneret alternatively '''Kinnereth''' or '''Chinnereth''', and sometimes in the plural as '''Chinneroth'''.<ref name=\"biblehub\">{{cite web|url=http://biblehub.com/topical/c/chinneroth.htm|website=biblehub.com|title=Bible Hub, ''Chinneroth'' |accessdate=2018-11-06}}</ref> The name became '''Gennesaret''' and '''Ginosar''' ({{Lang-he-n|\u05d2\u05b4\u05bc\u05e0\u05b5\u05bc\u05d9\u05e1\u05b7\u05e8}}). The remains of Kinneret have been excavated at a site called '''Tell el-'Oreimeh''' in [[Arabic]] and '''Tel Kinrot''' in [[Modern Hebrew]].\n\n==Etymology==\nKinneret, in the plural Kinnerot, was [[Grecized]] to Gennesaret, and Ginosar is yet another transformation of the name.<ref name=\"Easton\">Easton's Revised Bible Dictionary, [https://www.biblestudytools.com/dictionary/gennesaret  \"Gennesaret\"]</ref> According to the [[Jerusalem Talmud]] (Megillah 1:1), the name Kinneret is derived from the name of the ''kinnar'' trees which grow in its vicinity, explained by lexicographer [[M. Jastrow]] to mean the Christ's thorn jujube ([[Ziziphus spina-christi]]),<ref>Marcus Jastrow, ''Dictionary of the Targumim, the Talmud Babli and Yerushalmi, and the Midrashic Literature'', Peabody, Mass. 2006, p. 651 (s.v. '''\u05db\u05e0\u05e8\u05d0''')</ref> and by [[Moses Margolies]] to mean cane reeds.<ref>Jerusalem Talmud, ''Megillah'' 1:1 [2b]</ref> Others say that it is so-called because its fruits are as sweet as those of the ''kinnara'' (Ziziphus spina-christi).<ref>[[Babylonian Talmud]] (''Megillah'' 6a)</ref>\n\n===The lake===\nDue to its prominence, the city gave its name to the lake (the \"[[Sea of Galilee]]\") for long periods of history, as the Sea of Kinneret, Kinnerot, Gennesaret, or Ginosar.<ref name=\"Easton\"/> As other places around the lake rose to prominence, such as [[Tiberias]] and [[Khirbat al-Minya|Qasr al-Minya]], the name of the lake also changed to Lake Tiberias or Lake Minya.\n\n===The plain===\nThe name has also been used for the \"Plain of Gennesaret\", which stretches south of the ancient city. The plain's modern names are Plain of Ginosar in Hebrew and el-Ghuweir in Arabic.\n\n===Modern settlements===\nThe Israeli [[kibbutz]] [[Ginosar]] derives its name from the ancient town, though it is not located on its precise site. The settlements of [[Kinneret, Israel|Moshavat Kinneret]] and [[Kvutzat Kinneret]] are even further south, on the southwestern shore of the lake.\n\n==Identification and location==\n[[File:Grimm, J.L. Mahlmann, H. Tiberias. 1850-3.jpg|thumb|The Plain of Gennesaret marked on an 1850 German map of the Sea of Galilee as \"El-Ghuweir / Genezareth\" (western shore, stretching from \"[[Khirbat al-Minya|Khan Minyeh]]\" to \"el-Mejdel / Magdala\")]]\nThe site of the fortified [[Bronze Age|Bronze]] and [[Iron Age]] city of Kinneret is identified with the mound known in Arabic as Tell el-'Oreimeh and in modern Hebrew as Tel Kinrot, halfway between [[Capernaum]] and [[Magdala]].<ref name=Negev>{{cite book |editor=Avraham Negev, Shimon Gibson |year=2001 |title=Archaeological Encyclopedia of the Holy Land |location=New York, London |publisher=Continuum |page=285 |isbn=0-8264-1316-1 }}</ref><ref>Lamar Williamson 1983 ''Mark'' {{ISBN|0804231214}} pages 129-130</ref> Situated on an important trade route, its elevated position meant that it also overlooked and guarded the Plain of Ginosar from its northern end.\n\nThe [[Tell (archaeology)|tell]] is being excavated as part of a large archaeological project which is ongoing since 2002.<ref name=\"kinneret-excavations\">{{cite web|url=http://kinneret-excavations.org/?page_id=54|title=Tel Kinrot &#8211; Kinneret Regional Project|website=kinneret-excavations.org|accessdate=2018-11-06}}</ref> It has the [[Israeli Cassini Soldner|ICS Coordinates]]: 200805-1252830;<ref name=aharoni>[[Yohanan Aharoni|Aharoni, Yochanan]]. ''The Land of the Bible, A Historical Geography''. The Westminster Press, Philadelphia, 1979, p. 433.</ref><ref name=\"amudanan\">{{cite web|url=http://amudanan.co.il/|title=\u05e2\u05de\u05d5\u05d3 \u05e2\u05e0\u05df - \u05d4\u05de\u05d3\u05e8\u05d9\u05da \u05d4\u05e9\u05d9\u05ea\u05d5\u05e4\u05d9 \u05dc\u05d9\u05d3\u05d9\u05e2\u05ea \u05d4\u05d0\u05e8\u05e5|website=amudanan.co.il|lang=he|accessdate=2018-11-06}}</ref><ref name=coordinate-converter /> ca. 32.87000 N, 35.539312 E.<ref name=coordinate-converter>{{cite web|url=http://twcc.free.fr/|author=Cl\u00e9ment RONZON|website=twcc.free.fr|title=TWCC, The World Coordinate Converter|accessdate=2018-11-06}}</ref>\n\n==In the Bible==\nKinneret was a town allotted to the tribe of GAD ({{Bibleref2|Joshua 19:35}}). The name appears in the singular form as \"Kinneret\" ({{Bibleref2|Numbers 34:11}}, {{Bibleref2|Deuteronomy 3:17}}) or in the plural as \"Kinneroth\" ({{Bibleref2|Joshua 11:2, 12:3}}). In the [[New Testament]] the name appears changed to Gennesaret ({{Bibleref2|Luke 5:1}}).\n\nThis city or area is also a place where [[Jesus]] visited and performed healing.<ref>Matthew 14:34; Mark 6:53</ref> To quote from the Douay-Rheims Bible, which uses the form \"Genesar\" (see [[Gospel of Matthew]]),\n:[34] And having passed the water, they came into the country of Genesar. \n:[35] And when the men of that place had knowledge of him, they sent into all that country, and brought to him all that were diseased. \n:[36] And they besought him that they might touch but the hem of his garment. And as many as touched, were made whole.  ([http://drbo.org/chapter/47014.htm Matthew 14]:34-36).\n:\n:\n:\n:\n:\n\n==Other sources==\n{{hiero|knn\ua723rtw<ref name = Gauthier205/><ref name = Budge1048>{{cite book |last1=Wallis Budge |first1=E. A. |title=An Egyptian hieroglyphic dictionary: with an index of English words, king list and geological list with indexes, list of hieroglyphic characters, coptic and semitic alphabets, etc. Vol II |date=1920 |publisher=[[John Murray (publisher)|John Murray]] |page=[https://archive.org/details/egyptianhierogly02budguoft/page/1048 1048] |url=https://archive.org/details/egyptianhierogly02budguoft}}</ref>|<center><hiero>V31:N35-N35:G1-D21:Z1-X1-G43</hiero></center>|era=nk|align=right}}\nKinneret is mentioned as '''Kennartou''' in the [[Annals of Thutmose III]] at [[Temple of Karnak]].<ref name = Gauthier205>{{cite book |last1=Gauthier |first1=Henri |title=Dictionnaire des Noms G\u00e9ographiques Contenus dans les Textes Hi\u00e9roglyphiques Vol. 5 |date=1928 |page=205 |url=https://archive.org/details/Gauthier1928/page/n105}}</ref> [[Josephus|Flavius Josephus]], as well as the [[Babylonian Talmud]] mention the lake by the name \"Sea of Ginosar\" after the small fertile plain of Ginosar that lies at the foot of Tell el-'Oreimeh, ancient Kinneret. Josephus refers to the area as having very rich soil.<ref>''The Physical Geography, Geology, and Meteorology of the Holyand'' by [[Henry Baker Tristram]] 2007 {{ISBN|1593334826}} page 11</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Cities in the Book of Joshua]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[[Easton's Bible Dictionary (1897)]]\n*[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/06415a.htm Catholic Encyclopedia]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|Tel Kinarot}}\n*[http://kinneret-excavations.org/?page_id=54 Tel Kinrot page on the website of the \"Kinneret Regional Project\" international archaeological expedition]\n\n{{New Testament places associated with Jesus}}\n\n[[Category:New Testament places]]\n[[Category:Hebrew Bible places]]\n[[Category:Former populated places in Southwest Asia]]\n[[Category:Tells]]\n", "name_user": "CaeserKaiser", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kinneret_(archaeological_site)"}
